            "answer_text": "Q: Has anyone ever considered to restart the Pahlavi script to write Persian? This would be from all possible perspectives a bad idea. Pahlavi script was essentialy taken from the Aramaic writing system with a very low level of customisation for the needs of Iranic languages. Pahlavi with its mere 22 letters was even less practical writing system for any Iranic language than the current Perso-Arabic script (which is also not super ideal for Iranic languages). It was in no way reader-friendly. Already the people of Sassanian era were dissatisfied with the qualitative limits of Pahlavi script, for this reason Zoroastrian priestly scholars started to develop a better alphabetic writing system, and they invented the script known as Din Dabireh (\u201cScript of the Faith\u201d), enabling to clearly express all kinds of both consonants and vowels in a written form. The first version of Din Dabireh was used for the writing of Avestan texts, this version is also known as Avestan alphabet. The other version of Din Dabireh was customized for the writing in (Middle) Persian language (which did not necessarily need some of the Avestan letters, yet on the other hand it needed \u201cL\u201d letter which does not exist in Avestan language), this version is known as Pazend alphabet.  Pazend version of Din Dabireh If anything, Persian-customized version of Din Dabireh which would be able to provide an improved reading comfort if compared to the current script should be introduced, not Pahlavi script which was already in the ancient times seen as unsatisfactory. In contrast to Pahlavi, Din Dabireh was also born from a creative and scholarly effort of Iranians themselves. ",
