                "name": "Tanin Loker",
                "href": "/profile/Tanin-Loker"
            },
            "answer_text": "If you are interested in a scientific answer: Many people don\u2019t realise that the Pahlavi script is a very defective script, as many sounds are written with the same letter (e.g. D, Y, G are written with the same letter, as are R, W, N), which means that for some words there are more than 200 different readings (which makes the script essentially like Chinese characters, i.e. you have to know the image). Furthermore, (short) vowels are not written, many letters look similar and the orthography is convoluted (this last point could be fixed). Thus the Pahlavi script is much more difficult to handle than even the already not too easy Arabic script. Most attempts aiming at the reintroduction of a national script for the Persian and other Iranian languages use the much simpler Avestan alphabet as a model. ",
